  "prompt": "How does a hydraulic brake work? Describe in brief",
  "response": "A hydraulic brake works by using brake fluid to transmit force from the brake lever or pedal to the brake pads. When the brake is applied, the lever or pedal pushes a piston in the master cylinder, which pressurizes the brake fluid. This pressure is transmitted through the brake lines to the slave cylinder or caliper, where another piston forces the brake pads against the rotor or drum, slowing or stopping the vehicle. When the brake is released, the pressure is relieved, and the pads return to their original position, ready for the next application.",
